{"title":"Harmonic Oscillator Schrödinger Equation","markdown":{"headingText":"Harmonic Oscillator Schrödinger Equation","containsRefs":false,"markdown":"## Harmonic Oscillator Schrödinger Equation (4:17) { .unnumbered}\n<iframe style=\"width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 16/9\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Y1Y7Pvkz4fo\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n::: {.content-hidden unless-format=\"pdf\"}\n![YouTubeThumbnail](\"https://faculty.fairfield.edu/mkubasik/images/fairfielduShield.o.png\")\n:::\n\n\n\n::: {.callout-note}\nYou will find more excellent videos at this content creater's [YouTube Channel](https://www.youtube.com/@PhysicalChemistry)\n:::\n\n\n    \n## Harmonic Oscillator Schrödinger Equation  Video Transcript { .unnumbered}\n\n\nOkay, so let's put some pieces together and use our harmonic oscillator model. The potential energy for a harmonic oscillator will be inserted into the Schrödinger equation as we begin to solve that quantum mechanical problem. We know the Schrödinger equation in a couple of different forms, which are different ways of looking at the same equation. The Hamiltonian acts on a wave function to give us back an energy times the same wave function. The Hamiltonian always has the form \n\n\\[\n-\\frac{h^2}{8\\pi^2 m} \\frac{d^2}{dx^2}\n\\]\n\nwhere $m$ for a diatomic molecule is the reduced mass. This represents our kinetic energy term. We add to that the potential energy, multiplying the wave function, and that should equal energy times the wave function if that function indeed solves Schrödinger's equation.\n\nFor us, particularly when talking about the harmonic oscillator, our potential energy has the form \n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{2} k x^2.\n\\]\n\nSo, I'll just rewrite that one more time: our potential energy looks like \n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{2} k x^2\n\\]\n\nmultiplying a wave function. \n\nHere’s the version of Schrödinger's equation for the harmonic oscillator. I've used the harmonic oscillator potential energy \n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{2} k x^2.\n\\]\n\nNotice that the function we are solving Schrödinger's equation for is a function of $x$; it is a one-dimensional function. Each of these wave functions is just $\\psi(x)$, and Schrödinger's equation tells us we are looking for a function that, if we take these derivatives and multiply by the constants times the second derivative, add it to a quadratic function multiplying the wave function, we should get back the original function. \n\nSo, that is the differential equation we need to solve. This one has a different character than the ones we solved before because of the $x^2$ in the potential energy. That is the next task we have to solve, and we will do that in a separate video lecture. \n\nBut let me encourage you, before you get to that next video lecture, to ask yourself: what would that function look like? What types of functions are there that, if we take their second derivatives and add them to $x^2$ times the function, some things cancel and we get back the original function? \n\nFor example, if you want some things to try, we have seen before that $\\sin(x)$ or $\\sin(a x)$ seemed to be good at solving the rigid rotor and the particle in a box function. So, is that what our wave function should look like? Alternatively, maybe the wave function looks like some polynomial. \n\nLet’s say, for instance, $\\sin(a x)$ or $a x^3$ or $a x^4$ times a different constant. So, maybe $\\psi$ is a polynomial; it could involve $x^4, x^3, x^2$, or some polynomial involving powers of $x$. That is another typical option for what a function might look like. \n\nYou can also consider exponential functions, $e^{a x}$. Some function of this type is going to end up being useful to solve Schrödinger's equation. I encourage you, before you move on to the next video, to go ahead and take some second derivatives, add them to $x^2$ times these functions, or at least do as much of that math as you need to decide whether this will or won't solve Schrödinger's equation with the harmonic oscillator potential energy. \n\nAfter you've done that, I'll see you in the next video lecture, where we'll explore what these solutions do in fact look like.\n\n\n{{< include ../_text1.qmd >}}\n\n{{< include ../_text2.qmd >}}\n\n{{< include ../_footer.qmd >}}\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":false,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":"none","code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":false,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-tools":false,"tbl-colwidths":"auto","merge-includes":true,"inline-includes":false,"preserve-yaml":false,"latex-auto-mk":true,"latex-auto-install":true,"latex-clean":true,"latex-min-runs":1,"latex-max-runs":10,"latex-makeindex":"makeindex","latex-makeindex-opts":[],"latex-tlmgr-opts":[],"latex-input-paths":[],"latex-output-dir":null,"link-external-icon":false,"link-external-newwindow":false,"self-contained-math":false,"format-resources":[],"notebook-links":true},"pandoc":{"standalone":true,"wrap":"none","default-image-extension":"png","to":"html","toc":true,"toc-depth":3,"number-sections":true,"output-file":"Harmonic_Oscillator_Schrodinger_Equation.html"},"language":{"toc-title-document":"Table of contents","toc-title-website":"On thi